					<h4>Independent Booksellers</h4>
		
		<h1>Weighing in on the Tattered Cover&#8217;s Move</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 8-07-06</p>
			
			
							Colorado book lovers have taken plenty of interest in the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.tatteredcover.com/NASApp/store/IndexJsp" title="Tattered Cover's">Tattered Cover's</a> recent move from its Cherry Creek location to its new Colfax store in the former Lowenstein Theater.  In this <a target="_blank" href="http://bookstories.org/bookstories20060710.html" title="video podcast">video podcast</a>, owner Joyce Meskis explains the reasons behind the move and viewers can see video footage of the exciting book-moving process.  In <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/spotlight_columnists/article/0,2777,DRMN_23962_4894290,00.html" title="her column">her column</a> in Saturday's <i>Rocky Mountain News</i>, books editor Patti Thorn gives a positive review of the new store, while lamenting the loss of "the sense of grandeur and distinctiveness that comes with size."  Another measure of the store's stature among its patrons is the fact that it boasts its own <a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tattered_Cover" title="Wikipedia entry">Wikipedia entry</a>, and plenty of bloggers have weighed in on the move, too, including <a target="_blank" href="http://livebythefoma.blogspot.com/2006/08/booksfirst-july-2006.html" title="this fellow">this fellow</a> who made a pilgrimage all the way from Maryland to visit the store and booked a hotel room in Cherry Creek "so we would be close to the main Tattered Cover location only to find out that they had moved the entire store lock, stock, and barrel to a converted theater on Colfax Avenue."
						<b>[End of article]</b>
		</div>

